<h2>how can I protect myself?</h2>
<p>Fortunately, there is a lot you can do right now to protect yourself.</p>
<p>Layer 2 networks (L2s for short) have been designed to improve scaling on Ethereum. However, a well chosen L2 is also your best defense against MEV.</p>
<p>By moving your activities to a MEV minimizing L2 wherever possible, you are removing MEV opportunities from the Ethereum blockchain. Doing this:</p>
<p>Protects you from being exploited</p>
<p>Costs less in transaction fees</p>
<p>Reduces the centralizing effects of MEV on the Ethereum base layer</p>
<p>It's good for you, and it's good for the network.</p>
<p>It is important to note that most L2s are currently trusted, not decentralized. As such it is important to choose an L2 you can trust.</p>

<h2>which L2 do I choose?</h2>
<p>That’s coming! Zeromev intends to produce comparison data on the MEV performance of different L2s in due course.</p>
<p>Until then, we advise you to consider how committed to fair-ordering and frontrunning minimization different L2s are, and that you are aware of the MEV policy of any L2 you consider.</p>
<p>For example, Arbitrum has made it clear that front-running will not be tolerated whereas Optimism has looked to extract MEV from users by design.</p>

